ce. Women’s own experience of oppressive patriarchy bonded them with animals, who equally suffered from the dominance of masculine values in society, and from an assumption that all-powerful humans were entitled to exploit animals at will.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnimal rights activistszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aAnimal rights movementzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aAnimal welfarezGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen political activistszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aWomen.  aanimals.  abirds.  acruelty.  agender.  apatriarchy.  aprotection.  asentiment.  asympathy.  avivisection.1 aDonald, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packagez978311128249740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616229840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526162298423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526162298/original  a978-3-11-128249-7  Manchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packageb2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles